"Smythe-Wright D., Boswell S.M., Breithaupt P., Davidson R.D., Dimmer C.H., Diaz L.B.E.","Methyl iodide production in the ocean: Implications for climate change",2006,"Global Biogeochemical Cycles","20","3", GB3003,"","",,,10.1029/2005GB002642,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34248575297&partnerID=40&md5=6b663722c1a925d21c93ad5d93e98d6b","National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom; School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol, United Kingdom; National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantocks Close, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom","Smythe-Wright, D., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Boswell, S.M., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Breithaupt, P., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Davidson, R.D., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom; Dimmer, C.H., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol, United Kingdom, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Cantocks Close, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Diaz, L.B.E., National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, Southampton, United Kingdom, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, European Way, Southampton SO14 3ZH, United Kingdom","Methyl iodide concentrations of up to 45 pmol L-1, which flux into the marine boundary layer, have been found in low latitude waters of the Atlantic and Indian oceans. These high concentrations correlate well with the abundance of Prochlorococcus, and we have confirmed the release of methyl iodide by this species in laboratory culture experiments. Extrapolating, we estimate the global ocean flux of iodine to the marine boundary layer from this single source to be 5.3 × 1011 g I yr-1, which is a large fraction of the previously estimated total global flux and the implications are far reaching. Climate prediction models suggest increases in sea surface temperature and changes in biogeographical provenances in response to global warming. Such changes are likely to increase the abundance of Prochlorococcus, and we estimate a concomitant ∼15% increase in the release of iodine species to the atmosphere. Potentially, this could help mitigate global warming. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Boundary layers; Climate change; Concentration (process); Extrapolation; Iodine; Mathematical models; Oceanography; abundance; bacterium; biogeography; biological production; boundary layer; climate change; climate modeling; concentration (composition); global warming; laboratory method; marine environment; mitigation; organic compound; sea surface temperature; Atlantic Ocean; Indian Ocean; Prochlorococcus",,,,,,"Alicke, B., Hebestreit, K., Stutz, J., Platt, U., Iodine oxide in the marine boundary layer (1999) Nature, 397, pp. 572-573; Allan, B. J., G. McFiggans, C. Plane, and H. Coe (2000), Observations of iodine monoxide in the remote marine boundary layer, J. Geophys. Res., 105, 14,363-14,369Amachi, S., Kamagata, Y., Kanagawa, T., Muramatsu, Y., Bacteria mediate methylation of iodine in marine and terrestrial environments (2001) Appl. Environ. Microbiol, 67, pp. 2718-2722; Baker, A.R., Turner, S.M., Broadgate, W.J., Thompson, A., McFiggans, G.B., Vesperini, O., Distribution and sea-air fluxes of biogenic trace gases in the eastern Atlantic Ocean (2000) Global Bioseochem. Cycles, 14, pp. 871-886; Baker, J.M., Sturges, W.T., Sugier, J., Sunnenberg, G., Lovett, A.A., Reeves, C.E., 